{
  "answer": "In classical Urdu poetry, as represented in the Falsafa corpus (e.g., the *ghazals* of Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, Mirza Ghalib, and Allama Iqbal), *faqir* (also rendered as *faqeer* or *faqeeron*) typically refers to a mendicant, beggar-saint, or ascetic—often a Sufi figure who adopts poverty and renunciation (*faqri*) as a path to divine love and spiritual detachment from worldly comforts.[^1] Poets frequently invoke the *faqir* archetype to explore themes of true devotion versus hypocrisy: the ideal *faqir* or dervish pursues rigorous spiritual discipline, but a false one clings to ease or material desires.[^2]\n\nFor instance, Zauq contrasts the authentic dervish, who thrives on ascetic rigor (*riyazat*), with the *faqir* who secretly craves comfort (*rahat-parast*): \"The true Dervish is one who strives in sacred chore; / The mendicant renounces naught; a comfort-devotee is.\"[^3]\n\nIqbal praises serving *faqeeron* (humble sages or mendicants) to attain profound heartache (*dard-e-dil*), a treasure absent from kings' vaults.[^4] Ghalib employs *faqeeron* more ironically or metaphorically, as in the \"guise of mendicants\" assumed to witness generosity, or the *faqir*'s enduring \"youthful mischief\" even in life's ashes.[^5]\n\nThese usages reflect the Sufi-influenced ideal of *faqri* (spiritual poverty) central to Urdu poetic tradition, where the *faqir* embodies detachment yet risks critique for insincerity.\n\n[^1]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [ch. 25](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/25-kab-haq-parast-zahid-e-jannat-parast-hai/translation/#p-ef4ce6).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [ch. 90](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/90-jahan-tera-naqsh-e-qadam-dekhte-hain/translation/#p-6b3ee1).\n\n[^3]: Sheikh Ibrahim Zauq, *Diwan-E-Zauq*, [p-e44bc0](/works/sheikh-ibrahim-zauq-diwan-e-zauq-0fa798/25-kab-haq-parast-zahid-e-jannat-parast-hai/translation/#p-e44bc0).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [p-122a23](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/04-jinhein-main-dhoondta-tha-aasmanon-mein-zameenon-m/translation/#p-122a23).\n\n[^5]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [ch. 98](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/98-junoon-tohmat-kash-e-taskeen-na-ho-gar-shadmani-ki/translation/#p-c4765b).",
